browser session state worktree common-dir rooting (gm-method, plugkit-wasm-wrapper.js): SYMPTOM a workflow worktree fan-out (isolation:'worktree', each parallel agent in its own .claude/worktrees/wf_* worktree) opened ONE chromium PER worktree -- the 'meant to open one, got N browsers' defect. ROOT CAUSE browserStateDir(cwd)=<cwd>/.gm/exec-spool/browser-ports.json and sessionProfileDir(cwd,sid)=<cwd>/.gm/browser-profile-<slug> both keyed on process.cwd(), which in a worktree is the worktree root, so each agent had its own ports registry + profile + chromium (sessionId was even the same 'default' -- the discriminator was purely cwd). Witnessed by Win32_Process: distinct top-level user-data-dirs under sibling worktrees, each one chromium (the extra chrome.exe are that browser's normal gpu/renderer/utility children, same port, no own --user-data-dir -- so '4 browsers' in Task Manager can be ONE launch's multiprocess; confirm by counting distinct user-data-dir + MainWindowTitle, not raw chrome.exe count). FIX added browserRootDir(cwd): path.resolve(start) then spawnSync git rev-parse --git-common-dir; if the common dir ends in .git its dirname is the main repo root; path.resolve-normalize the result (a separator mismatch -- worktree giving C:/dev/x vs main C:\dev\x -- would key two registries on one dir, so normalize both); cache per-cwd; non-git falls back to cwd. Routed browserStateDir + sessionProfileDir + acquireProfileDir (+ its ensureGitignored target) + cleanDeadProfileFragments through it. RESULT all worktrees of one workflow resolve to the identical main-repo root -> share ONE browser-ports.json + profile + chromium; separate repos stay isolated. Sharing the registry makes the spawn a concurrency surface, so getOrCreateBrowserSession now wraps the reuse-recheck+spawn in an atomic O_EXCL single-flight lock (.browser-spawn-<slug>.lock, pid|ts body, staleness takeover, loser waits + attaches to the winner's wsEndpoint) -- per the every-single-instance-guard-is-atomic rule. gm-plugkit JS only (ships via gm-plugkit npm publish + watcher restart; NO wasm/cascade rebuild). LESSON any per-session resource (browser, profile, lock, registry) keyed on process.cwd() multiplies across worktree fan-out -- root shared resources at the git common dir; rs-exec/rs-plugkit Rust are NOT involved (browser lifecycle is entirely wrapper JS).